  "stderr": "\n\nThe implementation of the validation bits-per-byte (val_bpb) calculation has a critical flaw in how it counts bytes for tokens with leading spaces.\n\nIn `build_sentencepiece_luts`, the code correctly identifies the SentencePiece leading-space marker using `piece.startswith(\"\u2581\")` (U+2581). However, when it calculates the byte length of the token, it does:\n```python\nif piece.startswith(\"\u2581\"):\n    has_leading_space_np[token_id] = True\n    piece = piece[1:]\nbase_bytes_np[token_id] = len(piece.encode(\"utf-8\"))\n```\nWhile it strips the boundary marker, it fails to add back the 1 byte for the actual space character that the marker represents. The byte count for the token is thus undercounted by 1 byte.\n\nLater, in `_accumulate_bpb`, the code does:\n```python\ntok_bytes = base_bytes_lut[y].to(torch.float64)\ntok_bytes += (has_leading_space_lut[y] & ~is_boundary_token_lut[x]).to(torch.float64)\n```\nThis attempts to add 1 byte back, but ONLY if the previous token (`x`) is NOT a boundary token. This logic is flawed because the space byte should always be counted as part of the token's raw text representation, regardless of the previous token. The space is an actual character in the original text that was encoded into the token.\n\nBecause the space byte is conditionally omitted, the total byte count (`byte_sum`) will be lower than the true number of UTF-8 bytes in the validation text. Since BPB is calculated as `(val_loss / ln(2)) * (total_tokens / total_bytes)`, an artificially low `total_bytes` inflates the `total_tokens / total_bytes` ratio, resulting in an incorrectly high (worse) BPB metric.",
